{
  "doc_id": "10435",
  "text": "Another humoral factor that may impact islet function is lipopolysaccharide (LPS). LPS is a component of the outer membrane of gram-negative bacteria. Diet-induced diabetes is associated with elevated circulating LPS levels through changes in the gut microbiota and increased gut permeability [CITATION_1] . LPS causes weight gain, insulin resistance and glucose intolerance in animal models [CITATION_2] . In islets, LPS decreases insulin gene expression through decreased PDX-1 and MafA expression [CITATION_3] , reduces glucose-stimulated insulin secretion [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and induces inflammatory cytokines [CITATION_6] . These phenomena are TLR4-dependent, leading to NF-kB activation [CITATION_7] .",
